      "message": "First of all, thanks for all the input here 👍\n\n\u003e Is there a compelling reason (if you have example of code that would benefit, please share it) to make this promote to the parent \nobject? \n\nI never saw a use-case for an append operation `/\u003d` to not append anything. That would make it a maybe-append operation and more complicated for review.\n\n\u003e  In a quick test, it does look like std::filesystem will promote an empty append to the parent.\n\nAs per your check, `std::filesystem::path` operates this way but our D-Bus use-case is slightly different. While it is common to find things like config files at different levels in the filesystem tree, D-Bus interface are usually found at a given level of depth. At least currently that is the case for most interfaces.\n\nWe cannot let `std::filesystem::path` do our homework here anyways because it appends a trailing `/`.\n\n```cpp\nstd::filesystem::path path(\"/xyz/openbmc_project/software\");\nstd::cout \u003c\u003c (path / \"\") \u003c\u003c std::endl;\n\n// \"/xyz/openbmc_project/software/\"\n```\n\n\u003e I agree, we could handle this case better.  I\u0027d advocate for \nthe resulting path being something like /\u003cinvalid_path\u003e\n\nI am ok with this alternative. Appending some error string which clearly describes what went wrong and preserves the user code intent to append a path segment.\n\nSomething like\n\n```\nsdbusplus::message::object_path path(\"/xyz/openbmc_project\");\n\npath /\u003d \"\";\n\n// path is now /xyz/openbmc_project/error_empty_string_append\n```\n\nThis lands us at the user code intended depth and preserves both the namespace path as well as what went wrong.\n\nKindly review again and check if the new revision is acceptable.",
